body:
I've dug through the xUnit source and I think I've found the source of this problem.

The issue lies in the [`DisposeTestClass` method](https://github.com/xunit/xunit/blob/master/src/xunit.execution/Extensions/ReflectionAbstractionExtensions.cs#L63) in the `ReflectionAbstractionExtentions` class:
```c#
public static void DisposeTestClass(this ITest test,
                                    object testClass,
                                    IMessageBus messageBus,
                                    ExecutionTimer timer,
                                    CancellationTokenSource cancellationTokenSource)
{
    var disposable = testClass as IDisposable;
    if (disposable == null)
        return;

    // ISSUE HERE - If QueueMessage returns false then the disposal won't occur.
    if (!messageBus.QueueMessage(new TestClassDisposeStarting(test)))
        cancellationTokenSource.Cancel();
    else
    {
        try
        {
            timer.Aggregate(disposable.Dispose);
        }
        finally
        {
            if (!messageBus.QueueMessage(new TestClassDisposeFinished(test)))
                cancellationTokenSource.Cancel();
        }
    }
}
```

Essentially, if the user requests test cancellation (ex via `Ctrl+C` in the console runner) the `QueueMessage` call could return false causing the test class to not be properly disposed of.

It seems to me that the `else` should be removed that way the test class is always disposed of even if `QueueMessage` returns false when sending the `TestClassDisposeStarting` message.

I can submit a merge request with this change later this week.

Just wanted to add a +1 because I've also stumbled upon this issue while testing some Kafka work. I'd love for this to be merged in. Currently my workaround is to register the CancelKeypress manually
```csharp
            Console.CancelKeyPress += (_, e) => {
                this.Dispose();
            };
```
in the constructor, but I assume that might only work for console-based test runners.

@bradwilson do I understand correctly that this will make `Dispose()` on the test class called when the test run in canceled? Will test methods be awaited though or killed mid-execution (which happens currently with `dotnet test` it seem)? For that I guess we'd still need `CancellationToken` support on test methods, as in #345.

And will be this shipped as part of v3 or also v2?

Thank you!

issue.body:
Currently a test with the following form can be created.

``` csharp
[Fact]
public async Task TestSomething()
{
}
```

It would be extremely helpful if the following signature was supported as well.

``` csharp
[Fact]
public async Task TestSomething(CancellationToken cancellationToken)
{
}
```

In the future, the provided `CancellationToken` might support being cancelled if the user manually cancels a test run before it is complete, or perhaps based on other criteria like a limit on the total number of test failures that can occur before cancelling a parallel test run.

For now, it would be perfectly acceptable to simply pass `CancellationToken.None` for the parameter if/when it is encountered.
